column3: textile
column4: furniture

column1: 2290NANA"C1=CN(C(=C(C1=O)O)C2=C(C(=O)C=CN2O)O)O""Orellanine or Orellanin is a pyridine N-oxide and a crystalline alkaloid that is found naturally in some lifeforms
column2: specifically certain fungi. It has been found in at least 34 types of mushrooms in the Cortinariaceae family. (S373)"

column1: 2291NANA"C[C@@H]1O[C@@H](C[C@H]1O)C[N+](C)(C)C""Muscarine
column2: L-(+)-muscarine
column3: or muscarin is a natural product found in certain mushrooms
column4: particularly in Inocybe and Clitocybe species
column5: such as the deadly C. dealbata. It was first isolated from Amanita muscaria in 1869. It was the first parasympathomimetic substance ever studied and causes profound activation of the peripheral parasympathetic nervous system that may end in convulsions and death. Muscarine has no effects on the central nervous system because it does not cross the blood-brain barrier due to its positively charged (polar) nitrogen ion. (S404)"

column1: 229295486119548611"C\C=N\N(C)C=O""Gyromitrin is a toxic and possibly carcinogenic chemical present in most members of the fungal genus Gyromitra
column2: most notably the false morel G. esculenta. In the body it is metabolized to monomethylhydrazine (MMH). (S407)"

column1: 2293108079108079"NC(CCC(=O)NC1(O)CC1)C(O)=O""Coprine (N5-1-hydroxycyclopropyl-L-glutamine) which metabolises to 1-aminocyclopropanol
column2: a closely-related chemical having the same metabolic effects
column3: occurs naturally in the otherwise edible mushroom
column4: the common ink cap (Coprinopsis atramentaria). Similar reactions have been recorded with Clitocybe clavipes and Boletus luridus
column5: although the agent in those species is unknown. (S410)"

column1: 2294NANA"N[C@H](C(O)=O)c1cc(O)no1""Ibotenic acid is a chemical compound that is naturally occurring in the mushrooms Amanita muscaria and Amanita pantherina
column2: among others. Ibotenic acid is a powerful neurotoxin that is used as a \"brain-lesioning agent\" and has shown to be highly neurotoxic when \"injected directly into the brains of mice and rats.\" In 1960's
column3: ibotenic acid was originally isolated from Amanita ibotengutake in Japan. A. ibotengutake is very like to A. pantherina. (S585)"

column1: 2295NANA"NCc1cc(O)no1""Muscimol (Agarin
column2: Pantherine) is the major psychoactive alkaloid present in many mushrooms of the Amanita genus. Unlike psilocybin
column3: a tryptamine
column4: muscimol is a potent
column5: selective agonist of the GABAA receptor. Amanita muscaria contains two main active ingredients
column6: Ibotenic acid and its derivative Muscimol. Muscimol is the product of the decarboxylation or drying of ibotenic acid and it is thought that muscimol is as much as ten times more potent than ibotenic acid. (S586)"

column1: 22961062410624"CN(C)CCC1=CNC2=C1C(=CC=C2)OP(=O)(O)O""Psilocybin (pronounced /ˌsaɪlɵˈsaɪbɪn/ SYE-lə-SYE-bin) (also known as psilocybine) is a hallucinogenic (entheogenic
column2: psychedelic) indole of the tryptamine family
column3: found in psilocybin mushrooms. It is present in hundreds of species of fungi
column4: including those of the genus Psilocybe
column5: such as Psilocybe cubensis and Psilocybe semilanceata
column6: but also reportedly isolated from a dozen or so other genera. Psilocybin mushrooms are commonly called \"sacred mushrooms
column7: \" \"magic mushrooms
column10: of psilocybin or psilocin has been outlawed in most countries across the globe. Proponents of its usage consider it to be an entheogen and a tool to supplement various types of practices for transcendence
column13: and psychedelic psychotherapy. The intensity and duration of entheogenic effects of psilocybin mushrooms are highly variable
column17: and set and setting. Though psilocybin rarely attracts much attention from mainstream media
column18: when it does the focus tends to be on the recreational use
column19: generally excluding any other uses of the drug. (S587)"

column1: 229749804980"CN(C)CCC1=CNC2=C1C(=CC=C2)O""Psilocin is a psychedelic (hallucinogenic) mushroom alkaloid. It is found in most psychedelic mushrooms together with its phosphorylated counterpart psilocybin. Psilocin is the pharmacologically active agent in the body after ingestion of psilocybin or psychedelic mushrooms. Ingestion produces  physiological effects similar to a sympathetic arousal state. (V390)"

229882238223"CN1CC(C=C2C1CC1=CNC3=CC=CC2=C13)C(=O)NC1(C)OC2(O)C3CCCN3C(=O)C(CC3=CC=CC=C3)N2C1=O""A vasoconstrictor found in ergot of Central Europe. It is an alpha-1 selective adrenergic agonist and is commonly used in the treatment of migraine disorders. [PubChem]"

column1: 256852810815281081"CCN(CC)C(=O)C(C#N)=CC1=CC(=C(O)C(O)=C1)[N+]([O-])=O""Entacapone is a catechol-O-methyl transferase inhibitor for the treatment of Parkinson's disease. When administered in conjunction with dopaminergic agents such as L-DOPA

column1: 2948NANA"[I-]""Iodine is a chemical element that has the symbol I and atomic number 53. Chemically

column4: the element does not occur in the free state in nature. As with all other halogens
column5: when freed from its compounds iodine forms diatomic molecules. Iodine naturally occurs in the environment chiefly as a dissolved iodide in seawater
column6: although it is also found in some minerals and soils. Iodine is an essential trace element for life
column7: mainly as constituents of the thyroid hormones
column8: thyroxine (T4) and triiodothyronine (T3). Iodine and its compounds are primarily used in medicine
